---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
const title = 'Lead Generation for Architects: How to Stop Waiting for the Phone | IPQmedia';
const description =
  'Most architecture firms run on referrals and hope. Here is how to actually generate qualified project enquiries on purpose, which channels work, and which ones quietly waste your money.';
---

<Base title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Lead generation for architects</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Most architecture firms have exactly one way to get clients: be good enough that
    people talk about you. It works. Right up until the month nobody does.
  </p>

  <p>
    Referrals are the best leads you will ever get. They show up warm, they already
    trust you, they close without a fight. No argument there. The problem is not that
    referrals are bad. The problem is you do not control the tap. You cannot decide to
    get three more next month because a project finished early and your team is sitting
    on its hands.
  </p>
  <p>
    Lead generation is the boring-sounding fix for that very un-boring problem. All it
    means is putting your work in front of the right people on purpose, instead of by
    accident, so the pipeline is something you run rather than something you hope for.
  </p>

  <h2>The clients you never hear from</h2>
  <p>
    Here is the part that should bother you. A large chunk of the people who would
    happily hire you never get the chance to. They do not know an architect is who they
    need yet, or how early to call one. They are not in anyone's referral conversation
    because they do not even know what to ask for. They are sitting on a real budget and
    a real project, quietly Googling, and they will hand it to whoever shows up first.
    Wait to be found and you simply never meet them.
  </p>

  <h2>Where your future clients actually are</h2>
  <h3>Paid social, and yes, your clients are on it</h3>
  <p>
    Every architect we talk to says some version of "my clients are not scrolling
    Instagram looking for an architect." They are right. Nobody opens Instagram hunting
    for a floor plan. But the homeowner planning a $2M renovation is absolutely on there
    at night, saving kitchens and staring at houses they wish were theirs. Meta lets you
    put your best work in front of those exact people, in your city, before they have
    typed a single search. It is the most reliable way to turn the tap up when you want
    more work.
  </p>
  <h3>Search</h3>
  <p>
    Someone typing "custom home architect" and their city into Google is not browsing.
    They are close to picking up the phone. Showing up for those searches, and giving
    them an obvious next step when they land, catches demand that already exists and is
    ready to move. (You are reading a page that does exactly that, by the way.)
  </p>
  <h3>Your website, which is probably costing you work</h3>
  <p>
    Most architecture websites are beautiful and useless. Gorgeous photography, a long
    scroll of projects, and no earthly idea what the visitor is supposed to do next. A
    portfolio is not a pitch. One clear way to start a conversation, put where interested
    people actually are on the page, will do more for your pipeline than another gallery.
  </p>
  <h3>Content and follow-up</h3>
  <p>
    People research for months before they hire. Answer the questions they ask early,
    what an architect actually does, what it costs, how long it takes, and you become the
    firm they already trust by the time they are ready. Then follow up. Most enquiries do
    not book on day one, and most firms send one email and quietly give up. The firms
    with full calendars are just the ones that kept showing up.
  </p>

  <h2>Where the money quietly disappears</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>The boost button. Meta's "boost" is a polite way of taking your budget and handing you likes from people who will never hire you. It is not targeting.</li>
    <li>Running ads to a portfolio page with no next step, so the interest you paid for evaporates.</li>
    <li>Treating every enquiry the same, instead of working out fast who actually fits.</li>
    <li>Giving up after one follow-up, on people who needed three months to decide.</li>
    <li>Chasing volume. More leads is not the goal. More of the right projects is, and they are not the same thing.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What a system actually looks like</h2>
  <p>
    Nothing here is complicated. A pipeline that works has four parts that talk to each
    other:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Attract.</strong> Get your work in front of the right homeowners in your market, on purpose.</li>
    <li><strong>Qualify.</strong> Sort the serious projects from the tire-kickers quickly, by budget, location, scope, and timing, so your time goes where it counts.</li>
    <li><strong>Book.</strong> Spend your hours in real consultations with people who fit, not chasing cold contacts who ghost.</li>
    <li><strong>Measure.</strong> Watch what each channel brings back and feed the winners. Drop the rest without sentiment.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The firms that are good at marketing are not the ones with the biggest budgets. They
    are the ones with this loop running while everyone else waits for the phone.
  </p>

  <h2>How much should you spend?</h2>
  <p>
    The industry likes to quote 3 to 5 percent of revenue, a bit more if you are small
    and trying to build momentum. Fine as a starting point. But the percentage matters
    far less than two questions: are you spending it on purpose, and do you know what
    comes back? A modest budget aimed well beats a big one sprayed around, every time.
  </p>

  <h2>A few honest answers</h2>
  <h3>How do architects actually get clients?</h3>
  <p>
    Referrals plus a system that does not depend on them: ads that reach the right
    homeowners, search that catches the ones already looking, a site that asks for the
    next step, and follow-up that does not quit after one try.
  </p>
  <h3>How fast does this work?</h3>
  <p>
    Paid channels can bring enquiries within weeks. Search and content take a few months
    and then keep paying you back. Run both and you get something now while you build
    something that lasts.
  </p>
  <h3>Does paid social really work for high-end residential?</h3>
  <p>
    It tends to work best there, because it is visual and it lets you reach wealthy
    homeowners in your area who are planning a project but have not started searching.
    The clients are already on the platform. They just have not seen your work yet.
  </p>

  <h2>You can decide when the phone rings</h2>
  <p>
    Or you can keep waiting for it. It will probably ring. Eventually. The whole point of
    a real lead system is that you stop leaving that to chance. If you would rather have
    it built and run for you than piece it together yourself, that is the part we handle
    for architecture firms.
  </p>
  <a class="cta-block" href="https://ipqmedia.com/book-a-call">Book a call with IPQmedia</a>
</Base>
